Results.
For each data set and each of the five competitive methods, we test a variety of different kğ‘˜k values (222, 444, 888, 161616, though due to the small number of classes in the Aircraft data set, we omit the size-161616 model there). In each case, we randomly generate 10,000 learning problems to evaluate each method, and the method is scored using accuracy on 50 positive and 50 negative examples. For the evaluation, we use five iterations of gradient descent. All results (including average accuracy, 95% confidence interval width) are given in Table 1. For comparison, a single MAML model achieved 60.78% accruacy on ImageNet ILSVRC-2012, 62.37% accuracy on the cross-domain bird recognition problem, and 64.92% and 65.95% accuracy on the aircraft and Omniglot problems.
